In `src/app/api/chat/route.ts`, the user message gets embedded **three separate times** via three separate OpenAI API calls:

```ts
const userEmbedding = await embed(message);           // embed #1 (for storage)
...
const [notes, pastMessages] = await Promise.all([
  retrieveNotes(message, { count: 8 }),                // embed #2 (inside retrieveNotes)
  retrievePastMessages(message, conversationId!, ...),  // embed #3 (inside retrievePastMessages)
]);
```

Each embed call is a network round-trip to OpenAI (~100-300ms) — this adds ~200-600ms of pure waste to every chat turn and 3x's your embedding bill.

**Fix:** embed once, pass the vector down.

```ts
// src/lib/rag.ts
export async function retrieveNotes(
  queryEmbedding: number[],
  options: { count?: number; threshold?: number } = {}
): Promise<RetrievedNote[]> {
  const supabase = createAdmin();
  const { data, error } = await supabase.rpc("match_vault_notes", {
    query_embedding: queryEmbedding as unknown as string,
    match_count: options.count ?? 8,
    similarity_threshold: options.threshold ?? 0.5,
  });
  if (error) { console.error("retrieveNotes error:", error); return []; }
  return (data as RetrievedNote[]) || [];
}
// same change for retrievePastMessages(queryEmbedding, conversationId, options)
```

```ts
// route.ts
const userEmbedding = await embed(message);
await admin.from("messages").insert({ ..., embedding: userEmbedding as unknown as string });

const [notes, pastMessages] = await Promise.all([
  retrieveNotes(userEmbedding, { count: 8 }),
  retrievePastMessages(userEmbedding, conversationId!, { count: 5 }),
]);
```

`src/lib/self-prompt.ts` fetches `silas_prompt_state` then `silas_prompt_versions` sequentially, on *every single chat request*, even though the active prompt rarely changes.

**Fix:** either a single joined RPC, or (simpler) an in-memory TTL cache invalidated on edit:

```ts
// src/lib/self-prompt.ts
let promptCache: { version: number; body: string; expiresAt: number } | null = null;
const PROMPT_TTL_MS = 30_000;

export async function getActivePrompt() {
  if (promptCache && promptCache.expiresAt > Date.now()) {
    return { version: promptCache.version, body: promptCache.body };
  }
  // ...existing fetch logic...
  promptCache = { version, body, expiresAt: Date.now() + PROMPT_TTL_MS };
  return { version, body };
}

// bust the cache whenever it changes
export async function applyEdit(...) {
  // ...on success:
  promptCache = null;
}
export async function revertTo(...) {
  // ...on success:
  promptCache = null;
}
```

`src/lib/vault.ts`:

```ts
const { data } = await supabase.from("vault_notes").select("*").not("content", "is", null).limit(500);
// shuffle in JS, slice(0, 20)
```

This drags full note `content` for 480 rows you throw away — expensive on a table with 7,000+ notes containing full markdown bodies. Push the randomness into SQL:

```sql
create or replace function sample_vault_notes(sample_count int)
returns setof vault_notes as $$
  select * from vault_notes where content is not null
  order by random() limit sample_count;
$$ language sql stable;
```

```ts
export async function sampleNotes(count = 20): Promise<VaultNote[]> {
  const supabase = createAdmin();
  const { data, error } = await supabase.rpc("sample_vault_notes", { sample_count: count });
  if (error || !data) { console.error("sampleNotes error:", error); return []; }
  return data as VaultNote[];
}
```

The React source for `ChatInterface` and `AuroraBrain` isn't in the provided context, so I can't point at specific lines — but given this is a **streaming SSE chat UI**, the highest-risk pattern is:

```tsx
// Anti-pattern likely present: one state array holding all messages,
// re-set on every SSE token
const [messages, setMessages] = useState<Message[]>([]);
// on each `delta` event:
setMessages(prev => {
  const updated = [...prev];
  updated[updated.length - 1].content += token; // mutates + full array re-render
  return updated;
});
```

This re-renders **every** rendered message component on every token (dozens of times per second during a stream).

**Fix pattern:**
```tsx
// Keep committed history separate from the in-flight stream buffer
const [messages, setMessages] = useState<Message[]>([]);
const [streamingText, setStreamingText] = useState("");

// Memoize message list items so old messages never re-render
const MessageItem = React.memo(function MessageItem({ msg }: { msg: Message }) {
  return <div>{msg.content}</div>;
});

// Only the streaming bubble re-renders on each token
{messages.map(m => <MessageItem key={m.id} msg={m} />)}
{streamingText && <div>{streamingText}</div>}
```

For high token rates, batch state updates with `requestAnimationFrame` rather than calling `setState` per SSE event:
```tsx
const bufferRef = useRef("");
const rafRef = useRef<number>();
function onDelta(token: string) {
  bufferRef.current += token;
  if (!rafRef.current) {
    rafRef.current = requestAnimationFrame(() => {
      setStreamingText(bufferRef.current);
      rafRef.current = undefined;
    });
  }
}
```

If `AuroraBrain` is a canvas/animation component mounted at the root layout, verify it cleans up its animation loop:
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  const id = requestAnimationFrame(loop);
  return () => cancelAnimationFrame(id); // don't leak on unmount
}, []);
```
(It's mounted once at root so this mostly matters for HMR/dev, but worth confirming.)

---

In `src/app/api/chat/route.ts`, the `ReadableStream`'s tool-round loop never checks whether the client disconnected:

```ts
for (let round = 0; round < MAX_TOOL_ROUNDS; round++) {
  const stream = await streamChat({ ... });
  for await (const event of stream) { ... controller.enqueue(...) }
  ...
}
```

If the user closes the tab or navigates away mid-stream, this keeps running server-side — burning Anthropic tokens, holding the `convo` array and `fullText` string in memory, and potentially throwing when `controller.enqueue` is called on a cancelled controller.

**Fix:**
```ts
const responseStream = new ReadableStream({
  async start(controller) {
    const signal = req.signal;
    try {
      for (let round = 0; round < MAX_TOOL_ROUNDS; round++) {
        if (signal.aborted) break;
        const stream = await streamChat({ ... });
        for await (const event of stream) {
          if (signal.aborted) break;
          if (event.type === "content_block_delta" && event.delta.type === "text_delta") {
            controller.enqueue(encoder.encode(`data: ${JSON.stringify({ type: "delta", text: event.delta.text })}\n\n`));
          }
        }
        if (signal.aborted) break;
        // ...
      }
    } finally {
      controller.close();
    }
  },
  cancel() {
    // ReadableStream calls this on client disconnect — nothing extra needed
    // as long as we're checking req.signal.aborted in the loop above.
  },
});
```

`extractAndSaveNote` is documented as "never blocks user-facing chat response," but if the (truncated) tail of `route.ts` does `await extractAndSaveNote(...)` before closing the stream, it adds a full extra Anthropic round trip to response latency for no user-visible benefit. Use Next's `after()` to run it post-response instead:

```ts
import { after } from "next/server";
// ...
after(() => extractAndSaveNote({ userMessage: message, assistantMessage: fullText, conversationId }));
```

